nnual_Commemoration_of_the_Congressional_Civil_Rights_Pilgrimage_%286997171405%29.jpg/1280px-March_4%2C_2012_47th_Annual_Commemoration_of_the_Congressional_Civil_Rights_Pilgrimage_%286997171405%29.jpg","full":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/1/15/March_4%2C_2012_47th_Annual_Commemoration_of_the_Congressional_Civil_Rights_Pilgrimage_%286997171405%29.jpg","cap":"March 4, 2012 47th Annual Commemoration of the Congressional Civil Rig","desc":"As part of the celebrations, EPA Administrator Lisa P. Jackson spoke at the Brown Chapel AME Church in Selma, Alabama. Her remarks as prepared US EPA photo by Eric Vance","credit":"USEPA Environmental-Protection-Agency · Public domain","pageUrl":"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:March_4,_2012_47th_Annual_Commemoration_of_the_Congressional_Civil_Rights_Pilgrimage_(6997171405).jpg"},{"url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/61/March_4%2C_2012_Administrator_Jackson_and_community_leaders_complete_the_crossing_of_the_Edmund_Pettus_Bridge_in_Selma%2C_Alabama_%286851045804%29.jpg/1280px-March_4%2C_2012_Administrator_Jackson_and_community_leaders_complete_the_crossing_of_the_Edmund_Pettus_Bridge_in_Selma%2C_Alabama_%286851045804%29.jpg","full":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/6/61/March_4%2C_2012_Administrator_Jackson_and_community_leaders_complete_the_crossing_of_the_Edmund_Pettus_Bridge_in_Selma%2C_Alabama_%286851045804%29.jpg","cap":"March 4, 2012 Administrator Jackson and community leaders complete the","desc":"Historic Places of the Civil Rights Movement: Selma to Montgomery March US EPA photo by Eric Vance","credit":"USEPA Environmental-Protection-Agency · Public domain","pageUrl":"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:March_4,_2012_Administrator_Jackson_and_community_leaders_complete_the_crossing_of_the_Edmund_Pettus_Bridge_in_Selma,_Alabama_(6851045804).jpg"},{"url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/4/4b/Edmund_Pettus_Bridge_%E2%80%9CBloody_Sunday%E2%80%9D_%287222972538%29.jpg","full":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/4/4b/Edmund_Pettus_Bridge_%E2%80%9CBloody_Sunday%E2%80%9D_%287222972538%29.jpg","cap":"Edmund Pettus Bridge “Bloody Sunday” (7222972538)","desc":"On “Bloody Sunday,” March 7, 1965, during a march to Montgomery, non-violent civil rights demonstrators were attacked by armed officers as they crossed this bridge. Captured on film and broadcasted across national television, the event left the nation in disbelief and increased awareness to the unfair voting practices that were taking place throughout the state.","credit":"TradingCardsNPS · CC BY 2.0","pageUrl":"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Edmund_Pettus_Bridge_%E2%80%9CBloody_Sunday%E2%80%9D_(7222972538).jpg"},{"url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/e/e8/Civil_Rights_Marchers_Selma_to_Montgomery_March_%287222972614%29.jpg","full":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/e/e8/Civil_Rights_Marchers_Selma_to_Montgomery_March_%287222972614%29.jpg","cap":"Civil Rights Marchers Selma to Montgomery March (7222972614)","desc":"March 21-25, 1965 On March 21, 1965, demonstrators began marching from Selma to Montgomery for voting rights. When they reached the Alabama State Capitol Building, their numbers exceeded 25,000. Nearly five months after Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. spoke from a stage near the capitol steps, the Voting Rights Act was signed by President Lyndon B. Johnson.","credit":"TradingCardsNPS · CC BY 2.0","pageUrl":"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Civil_Rights_Marchers_Selma_to_Montgomery_March_(7222972614).jpg"},{"url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0f/Edmund_Pettus_Bridge_-_National_Historic_Landmark_%2827808790671%29.jpg/1280px-Edmund_Pettus_Bridge_-_National_Historic_Landmark_%2827808790671%29.jpg","full":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/0/0f/Edmund_Pettus_Bridge_-_National_Historic_Landmark_%2827808790671%29.jpg","cap":"Edmund Pettus Bridge National Historic Landmark (27808790671)","desc":"A National Historic Landmark sign on the Edmund Pettus Bridge in Selma, Alabama.","credit":"Tony Webster from Minneapolis, Minnesota, United States · CC BY-SA 2.0","pageUrl":"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Edmund_Pettus_Bridge_-_National_Historic_Landmark_(27808790671).jpg"},{"url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e3/Bloody_Sunday_by_Ted_Ellis.jpg/1280px-Bloody_Sunday_by_Ted_Ellis.jpg","full":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/e/e3/Bloody_Sunday_by_Ted_Ellis.jpg","cap":"Bloody Sunday by Ted Ellis","desc":"This is the artwork of American artist, Ted Ellis","credit":"Ted Ellis · CC BY-SA 4.0","pageUrl":"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Bloody_Sunday_by_Ted_Ellis.jpg"},{"url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/c/c5/Selma_photo.jpg","full":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/c/c5/Selma_photo.jpg","cap":"Selma photo","desc":"Mark Denbeaux March towards Selma","credit":"I'm not sure who took the photo. · CC BY-SA 4.0","pageUrl":"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Selma_photo.jpg"},{"url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/1/1d/Introductory_Panel_for_the_Selma_to_Montgomery_Exhibit_-_NARA_-_16898955.jpg","full":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/1/1d/Introductory_Panel_for_the_Selma_to_Montgomery_Exhibit_-_NARA_-_16898955.jpg","cap":"Introductory Panel for the Selma to Montgomery Exhibit","desc":"","credit":"Public domain","pageUrl":"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Introductory_Panel_for_the_Selma_to_Montgomery_Exhibit_-_NARA_-_16898955.jpg"},{"url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/e/e8/Photograph_of_Dr._King_and_the_Front_Line_Marching_up_Dexter_Avenue_for_the_Final_Leg_to_the_Alabama_State_Capital_-_NARA_-_16899454.jpg","full":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/e/e8/Photograph_of_Dr._King_and_the_Front_Line_Marching_up_Dexter_Avenue_for_the_Final_Leg_to_the_Alabama_State_Capital_-_NARA_-_16899454.jpg",